                                <div id="principles-principles-1" style="line-height:2;font-size: 14pt;">
                                    <p class="fenix">In layman's terms, Green's Theorem says that the integral of something over the boundary of a region equals the integral of something else over the region itself.

                                        When we talk about the positive  orientation on the boundary of $S$, think of taking an arrow tangent to a circle and pointing in the positive direction of the curve, now when we turn it $90^{\circ}$ clockwise it should be pointing <i>out</i> of the circle.</p>
                                    <br>
                                    <br>    
                                    <ul style="list-style:none;">    
                                        <li>$S$: regular region in $\mathbb{R}$</li>
                                        <li>$\partial S$: piecewise smooth boundary of $S$</li>
                                        <li>$\vec{\mathbf{F}}$: vector field of class $C^1$ on $\bar{S}$</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <br>
                                    <br>
                                    <p class="fenix">
                                    Then:
                                    <br>
                                    <br>
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} \vec{\mathbf{F}} \cdot d\vec{\mathbf{x}} = \iint_S \left( \frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x_1} - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial x_2} \right) \ dA$$
                                    <br>
                                    Now if we let $\vec{\mathbf{F}}= \left( P, Q \right)$ and $\vec{\mathbf{x}} = (x, y)$, then
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} P \ dx + Q \ dy = \iint_S \left(  \frac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial P}{\partial y} \right) \ dA$$
                                    <br>
                                    Another way to see Green's Theorem is when we take the normal component of  $\mathbf{F}$, which is just the tangential component of $\mathbf{F}$ when it's rotated $90^{\circ}$ counterclockwise. 
                                    <br>
                                    Let $\vec{\mathbf{n(x)}}$ be the unit normal vector to $\partial S$ for all $\vec{\mathbf{x}}$ belonging to $\partial S$, then,
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} \vec{\mathbf{F}} \cdot \vec{\mathbf{n}} \ ds = \iint_S \left(  \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial x_1} + \frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x_2} \right)$$
                                    <br>
                                    In vector form, Green's theorem looks like
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} \vec{\mathbf{F}} \cdot d \vec{\mathbf{x}} = \iint_S \left( \nabla \times \vec{\mathbf{F}} \right) \cdot d \vec{\mathbf{x}}$$
                                    <br>
                                    Green's theorem can also be used to find the area of $S$ by way of line integrals. The area of $S$ is given by 
                                    $$A = \iint_S dA$$
                                    <br>
                                    To make it simple, let's conveniently choose 
                                    <br>
                                    $$  \frac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial P}{\partial y}  = 1$$
                                    Now, Green's theorem reduces to
                                    <br>
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} P \ dx + Q \ dy = \iint_S 1 \ dA$$
                                    So,
                                    $$\int_{\partial S} P \ dx + Q \ dy = A$$
                                    The area of $S$ can then be found by integrating
                                    $$A = \frac{1}{2} \int_{\partial S} \left( x \ dy - y \ dx \right)$$
                                    We get this result since 
                                    $$\frac{d}{dx} \left( \frac{x}{2} \right) = \frac{1}{2} \ \ \mathrm{and} \ \ \frac{d}{dy} \left( -\frac{y}{2} \right) = -\frac{1}{2}$$
                                    So, from above,
                                    $$\frac{1}{2} - \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right) = 1$$
                                    <br>
                                    <br>
                                    Green's theorem has close relationships to Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.</p>
